{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a module boundary (request builder -> API client payload). A unit test of only a helper can miss serialization/adapter handoff issues. Rejected higher levels: behavior text only requires request contents, not real network/OS ('request sent ... includes ... labels'), so System is disqualified; no dependence on model output quality, so Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module to a stub API client that records outbound payload. Invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert the captured request contains the full label set (no omissions/reordering loss due to wiring).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real risk is handoff from API response parsing/adapter into taxonomy validation and outward return value. A pure unit test of validator logic may miss response-shape mapping issues. Rejected higher levels: no real OS/network requirement in behavior text, and correctness does not depend on model judgment quality for this case (only handling an out-of-taxonomy value), so System/Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Use a stub API client returning a controlled raw response containing an invalid label. Call the module public classify entrypoint and assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\" and never the raw unexpected label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is explicitly about deterministic normalization for identical inputs, which is a local function/object boundary with no I/O. Higher levels are disqualified because text scopes to normalization step only, not network/model behavior.","test_description":"Call normalization directly multiple times with the same raw response fixture (including casing/whitespace variants where relevant) and assert identical normalized label each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency of returned labels, which depends on real model/provider outputs and potential non-determinism. Integration with stubs would hide this class of failure. Rejected Workflow: this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N real provider calls for the same (document, taxonomy) under fixed request settings, capture provider raw responses and module labels, and assert label changes only occur when provider response content changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is orchestration between token-budget logic and dispatch path (must enforce before send). Unit tests of tokenizer/policy alone can miss accidental dispatch despite over-budget state. Rejected System: behavior does not require real network/OS; a stub client can prove 'before dispatch' behavior. Rejected Agentic/Workflow: no dependence on model output quality or multi-agent sequence.","test_description":"Wire classifier to a stub client and configure a small budget. Provide documents that are under/over threshold and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) and that outbound dispatch behavior matches policy (e.g., no send on reject).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires real provider-reported usage from actual AI API execution; stubs cannot reveal drift/mismatch in provider token accounting versus configured budget. Rejected Workflow: single call budget validation, not multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls for representative 'typical' documents and assert provider usage metadata (prompt/total tokens per call) does not exceed configured budget threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.66,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is retry/backoff orchestration across module + API client + timing/retry policy; in-process stubs can reproduce 429/rate-limit signals and validate retry behavior. Rejected System: behavior text does not require real network conditions, only handling a signaled rate-limit response. Rejected Agentic/Workflow: depends on transport/control-flow handling, not model output quality or multi-agent sequencing.","test_description":"Use a controllable stub API client that returns rate-limit error first, then success. Assert module waits/backs off according to policy, retries expected count, and returns successful classification instead of surfacing immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
